In like manner, falsehood often becomes a source of pleasure in the process of teaching, not because it is false, but beca'use by true teach- ing it is shown to be false.¹ (D. D. C. IV, 12. 28.) And further- more, by the Plain Style is meant the simplicity of the language in which the thought is clothed, and the term does not apply to the thought which may be exceedingly difficult, as for example, Paul’s exposition of the law (D. D. C. IV, 20. 39), but to the phraseology, which must be purely didactic, and as far as possible, devoid of rhetorical ornament.

As regards simplicity of treatment being the essential charae- teristic of the Plain Style the following citations are noted:
